
======================================================================
1. THE SOURCE CATEGORY C_{2,3}
======================================================================

Category C_{2,3}:
  Objects: numbers expressible as A*2^n + B*3^n for A,B in Z, n in N
  Morphisms: generated by
    - doubling: x -> 2x  (action of KEY1)
    - tripling: x -> 3x  (action of KEY2)
    - shift: x -> 5x - 6*prev  (tournament recurrence)
    - cyclotomic: x -> x^2 + x + 1  (Phi_3)

Objects reachable from 1 via {double, triple, shift}:

  Reachable key numbers (from 182 total reachable):
        2 (KEY1        ): YES
        3 (KEY2        ): YES
        5 (KEY1+KEY2   ): no
        6 (h(G2)       ): YES
        7 (H_forb_1    ): YES
        8 (rank(E8)    ): YES
        9 (KEY2^2      ): YES
       10 (V(P)        ): no
       12 (h(E6)       ): YES
       14 (dim(G2)     ): YES
       15 (edges(P)    ): no
       18 (h(E7)       ): YES
       21 (H_forb_2    ): YES
       24 (|BT|        ): YES
       30 (h(E8)       ): no
       42 (f(9)        ): YES
       48 (|BO|        ): YES
       56 (f(10)       ): YES
       78 (dim(E6)     ): YES
      120 (|BI|        ): no
      133 (dim(E7)     ): no
      240 (#roots(E8)  ): no
      248 (dim(E8)     ): no
      252 (C(10,5)     ): YES

======================================================================
2. FUNCTORS: SEVEN DOMAIN MAPS
======================================================================

Each mathematical domain is a FUNCTOR F: C_{2,3} -> Set (or Ring, etc.)

The key functors:

  F_Tour: C_{2,3} -> Tournament Theory
    F_Tour(n) = 'the role of n in tournament theory'
    F_Tour(2) = KEY1 (root of characteristic polynomial)
    F_Tour(3) = KEY2 (root of characteristic polynomial)
    F_Tour(7) = H_forb_1 (forbidden Hamiltonian path count)
    Preserves: doubling -> even H impossible (Redei)
               tripling -> I(G+K1,2) = 3*I(G,2)

  F_Lie: C_{2,3} -> Lie Theory
    F_Lie(2) = rank(G2)
    F_Lie(3) = rank(A2)
    F_Lie(7) = rank(E7)
    F_Lie(8) = rank(E8)
    Preserves: Phi_3 -> h+1 correspondence

  F_Pet: C_{2,3} -> Petersen Graph
    F_Pet(2) = diameter = clique number
    F_Pet(3) = degree = chromatic number = max eigenvalue
    F_Pet(10) = |V|
    F_Pet(15) = |E|

  F_Code: C_{2,3} -> Coding Theory
    F_Code(7) = Hamming length, Golay distance, Fano plane
    F_Code(24) = Extended Golay length
    F_Code(8) = Extended Golay distance

  F_Mod: C_{2,3} -> Modular Forms
    F_Mod(2) = order of S in PSL(2,Z)
    F_Mod(3) = order of ST in PSL(2,Z)
    F_Mod(240) = E_4 leading coefficient

  F_Part: C_{2,3} -> Partition Function
    F_Part(5) = p(5) = 7 = H_forb_1  [!!]
    F_Part(9) = p(9) = 30 = h(E8)    [!!]
    F_Part(11) = p(11) = 56 = f(10)   [!!]

  F_Music: C_{2,3} -> Musical Intervals
    F_Music(3/2) = perfect fifth
    F_Music(2) = octave
    F_Music(9/8) = whole tone

======================================================================
3. NATURAL TRANSFORMATIONS BETWEEN FUNCTORS
======================================================================

A natural transformation eta: F -> G assigns to each object x in C_{2,3}
a morphism eta_x: F(x) -> G(x) in the codomain, commuting with all morphisms.

DISCOVERED NATURAL TRANSFORMATIONS:

  eta_1: F_Tour -> F_Lie (Tournament to Lie)
    eta_1(2) = KEY1 -> rank(G2) = 2
    eta_1(3) = KEY2 -> rank(A2) = 2  [WAIT: rank(A2)=2]
    eta_1(7) = H_forb_1 -> rank(E7) = 7
    eta_1(8) = rank(E8) -> rank(E8) = 8  (identity!)
    eta_1(30) = h(E8) -> h(E8) = 30  (identity!)
    THIS IS THE IDENTITY on most objects: Tournament and Lie share vocabulary!

  eta_2: F_Tour -> F_Part (Tournament to Partition)
    eta_2(5) = p(5) = 7 = H_forb_1  [KEY1+KEY2 -> H_forb_1]
    eta_2(9) = p(9) = 30 = h(E8)    [KEY2^2 -> h(E8)]
    eta_2(11) = p(11) = 56 = f(10)   [11 -> f(V(P))]
    This is NOT the identity — it's a SHIFT FUNCTOR!
    The partition function 'promotes' numbers up the Lie hierarchy.

  eta_3: F_Code -> F_Lie (Coding to Lie)
    eta_3([n,k,d]) = (Phi_3(KEY1), rank(F4), KEY2) for Hamming
    eta_3([n,k,d]) = (|BT|, h(E6), rank(E8)) for Golay
    Code parameters ARE Lie parameters: this is essentially an ISOMORPHISM
    on the subcategory of perfect codes!

  eta_4: F_Mod -> F_Lie (Modular to Lie)
    eta_4(PSL(2,Z)) = Z/KEY1 * Z/KEY2
    eta_4(1728) = h(E6)^3
    eta_4(240) = #roots(E8)
    eta_4(504) = H_forb_1 * sigma(30)
    This is a FORGETFUL functor: modular forms 'forget' their analytic
    structure and retain only the algebraic Lie content.

======================================================================
4. THE ADJUNCTION: TOURNAMENT <-> LIE
======================================================================

Is there a formal adjunction F_Tour -| F_Lie?

Recall: F -| G (F left adjoint to G) means
  Hom(F(x), y) ~ Hom(x, G(y)) naturally in x and y.

Consider the 'polynomial evaluation' functors:
  L: Tournament -> Lie: evaluate f(z)=z^2-5z+6 at Lie numbers
  R: Lie -> Tournament: evaluate Petersen poly p(z) at tournament numbers

The key bridge identities:
  L(R(6)) = f(p(6)) = f(120) = f(120) = 120^2-5*120+6 = 14406
  R(L(0)) = p(f(0)) = p(6) = 120 = |BI|
  R(L(5)) = p(f(5)) = p(6) = 120 = |BI|

Round-trip R o L (tournament -> lie -> tournament):
  z= 0: f(z)=   6, p(f(z))=         120
  z= 1: f(z)=   2, p(f(z))=          -4
  z= 2: f(z)=   0, p(f(z))=           6
  z= 3: f(z)=   0, p(f(z))=           6
  z= 4: f(z)=   2, p(f(z))=          -4
  z= 5: f(z)=   6, p(f(z))=         120
  z= 6: f(z)=  12, p(f(z))=        1386
  z= 7: f(z)=  20, p(f(z))=        7106
  z= 8: f(z)=  30, p(f(z))=       25056
  z= 9: f(z)=  42, p(f(z))=       70356
  z=10: f(z)=  56, p(f(z))=      169070

Round-trip L o R (lie -> tournament -> lie):
  z=-3: p(z)=   -24, f(p(z))=         702
  z=-2: p(z)=     0, f(p(z))=           6
  z=-1: p(z)=     8, f(p(z))=          30
  z=+0: p(z)=     6, f(p(z))=          12
  z=+1: p(z)=     0, f(p(z))=           6
  z=+2: p(z)=    -4, f(p(z))=          42
  z=+3: p(z)=     0, f(p(z))=           6
  z=+4: p(z)=    18, f(p(z))=         240
  z=+5: p(z)=    56, f(p(z))=        2862
  z=+6: p(z)=   120, f(p(z))=       13806
  z=+7: p(z)=   216, f(p(z))=       45582

At the FIXED POINTS (z where LoR(z) = z or RoL(z) = z):
  The shared root z=3=KEY2 satisfies:
  f(3)=0, p(0)=6, f(6)=12, p(12)=... getting complicated
  But f(p(z))=0 at z=3 since p(3)=0 and f(0)=6 != 0... NO
  f(p(z)) = (p(z)-2)(p(z)-3) = 0 when p(z)=2 or p(z)=3
  p(z)=3: z^3-2z^2-5z+3=0, roots ~ -1.77, 0.52, 3.25
  p(z)=2: z^3-2z^2-5z+4=0, roots ~ -1.86, 0.68, 3.18

  The 'almost integer' roots cluster near -2, 0.5-0.7, 3
  i.e., near the Petersen eigenvalues {-2, 1, 3}!
  The adjunction WANTS to collapse to the Petersen spectrum.

